Background
ultiple sclerosis () is a chronic inflammatory demyelinating disease of the central nervous system () with a progressive course. lthough the cause of  is unknown, it is regarded as a complex disease that results from the combined effect of unidentified environmental factors and susceptibility genes. n western countries, it represents the second most common cause of disability in young adults, with onset usually occurring in the third or fourth decade of life.  has an incidence of about 4 to 4.5 per 100.000 every year, an average prevalence of 83 per 100,000 in urope and a female-to-male ratio of about 3:1
[1].
 has a chronic course that evolves over 30 to 40 years. he clinical phenotypes include relapsing-remitting  (), secondary progressive  (), primary progressive  () and progressive relapsing  ()
[2]. he development of a progressive course is by far the major route to permanent long-term disability, and it supervenes in about 80% of patients with  by age 20 to 25 years. fter age 15 to 18 years, about 50% of patients need assistance to walk, are confined to a wheelchair or have died, but there is substantial variation
[3].
here are currently several pharmacological treatments approved for , but only one agent (interferon ²-1b) has been approved in urope (but not by the .. ood and rug dministration ()) for the  form
[4]. irst-line treatments for  patients are interferon ²-1a (-²-1a) and -1b and glatiramer acetate. he effect of these treatments is a moderate reduction in relapse rate and accumulation of disability at 1 to 2 yearsβ€™ follow-up
[5]. here is evidence of no effect of these treatments for patients with 
[6] and inconclusive evidence for those with 
[7]. ide effects of these treatments are common, including influenza-like symptoms, injection site reactions, headache, depression and fatigue. ematological toxic effects include hemoglobin reduction, leukopenia, lymphocytopenia, thrombocytopenia and increased liver enzymes
[5-7].
itoxantrone, natalizumab or fingolimod are second-line treatments for patients who have failed to respond to the first-line therapy. itoxantrone is moderately effective in reducing disability progression and relapse rate in patients with ,  and  at short-term follow-up (2 years), but there is a long-term risk of therapy-related leukemias and cardiotoxicity
[8]. atalizumab has been shown to be consistently effective in reducing the risk of relapses and disability progression after 2 years of treatment, but it increases the risk (not yet definitively assessed, but greater than 1 per 1,000 after 2 years of treatment) of progressive multifocal leukoencephalopathy
[9]. ingolimod was the first drug to gain approval as an oral treatment by the  and the uropean edicines gency () for reducing relapse rate, but it can cause serious herpetic infections
[10].
here is currently no available pharmacological treatment with a good profile of safety and tolerability that is able to change, surely and meaningfully, the natural course of . ther biologic agents have recently been evaluated in phase  clinical trials for  and seem to be more effective than interferons and glatiramer
[11], but more phase  trials are needed to provide conclusive evidence of their efficacy and safety.
 recent hypothesis suggests that the presence of stenosis of the internal jugular vein () and/or azygos veins that restricts normal blood flow from the brain and spinal cord may be an important factor in the pathogenesis of 
[12,13]. he multifocal perivenous inflammation or demyelination in the  is postulated to be a consequence of a breakdown of the bloodβ€“brain barrier due to elevated transmural pressure, followed by erythrocyte, plasma and iron extravasation, thus resulting in damage to the immune tolerance and setting off a cascade of inflammatory events and immune responses that can persist over time
[14]. ere this hypothesis tenable, repairing venous stenosis and reestablishing correct venous flow from the brain toward the heart could have therapeutic effects, especially if the intervention was performed early. his condition has been named β€�chronic cerebrospinal venous insufficiencyβ€� () and is postulated to be congenital and genetically determined. , as defined by amboni et al., is diagnosed with combined extracranial and transcranial echo color oppler () radiography when two or more of five established parameters are present
[12]. n 100% of the  cases examined by amboni and colleagues, at least two of these alterations were found, as compared to 0% among healthy controls and patients affected by other neurological diseases
[12]. ince publication of this first study, several articles have been published on the prevalence of  in patients with or without . o collect all the available information on , we have updated (through ay 2012) the results of a previous published meta-analysis
[15]. he included studies were conducted in taly, the nited tates, ermany, oland, ordan and ran
[12,16-29]. he results (igureβ€‰
1) indicate a statistically significant association between  and  (odds ratio = 4.90;  95% = 1.86 to 12.90). owever, the body of evidence is highly heterogeneous (2 = 85%) and thus inconclusive. he heterogeneity can be ascribed to various factors, including low-quality studies, mainly due to small sample sizes, inadequate study design and setting, absence of blindedness, varying accuracy of the , including equipment, parameters, probes, techniques used and examinersβ€™ experience.
igure 1eta-analysis of diagnosis of chronic cerebrospinal venous insufficiency (presence of at least two parameters according to amboni criteria in patients with multiple sclerosis ()) versus healthy controls.amboni et al.
[30] reported the results of an open study of endovascular treatment for  on 65  patients who had undergone percutaneous transluminal angioplasty () to widen the veins. he results of  were safe. atients with  (n = 35) had fewer relapses, and their  functional composite () scores significantly improved at 18 months after the intervention compared with baseline. atients with  (n = 20) or  (n = 10) showed little improvement in  score. ll patients had improvement of physical and mental health as measured by the  uality of ifeβ€“54 questionnaire at 18-month follow-up.  high incidence (47%) of restenosis in the  was reported at 18 months
[30]. n a case series of 24 patients, 6 patients had a relapse of clinical symptoms within 1 to 2 months of the procedure, although it was reported that they felt better than before the procedure
[31]. n a case series of 31  patients with ,  was performed in the azygos vein in 90% (28 of 31) of patients and in both the left and right s in 77% (24 of 31). cores on the odified atigue mpact cale () significantly improved from preoperative values, and the positive trend was maintained at 1 year
[32]. n a retrospective case series of 167 patients affected by  and  who underwent , 67% of patients reported subjective amelioration regarding nonspecific symptoms
[33]. n a caseβ€“control study, eight patients had  in addition to medical therapy (immediate treatment group ()), whereas seven had treatment with  after 6 months of medical therapy alone (delayed treatment group ()). o adverse events occurred. fter , a significant improvement in functional score compared with baseline was found ( < 0.02). he annualized relapse rate was 0.12% in the  group compared with 0.66% in the  ( = ns). agnetic resonance imaging () demonstrated a trend for fewer 2 lesions in the  ( = 0.081), corresponding to a 10% decrease in the  compared with a 23% increase in the  over the first 6 months of the study. t 1 year, there was a restenosis rate of 27%
