[35].  case series of 331 patients reported that 15 repeat procedures were done for reocclusions following balloon angioplasty
[36].  case series of 247 procedures (229 primary procedures and 18 secondary procedures due to restenosis) in 231 patients reported that 2% of patients had symptomatic stenosis that required retreatment within 30 days
[37].
egarding the safety of the intervention, the study by etrov
[35] reported vein dissection in 3% of procedures (15 of 495), vein rupture (resolved by prolonged balloon dilatation and stenting) in two patients and groin hematoma in 1% of procedures (5 of 495). he same study reported cardiac arrhythmias in 1% of procedures (6 of 495). hese included atrial fibrillation in four patients (two resolved spontaneously and two resolved following treatment with amiodarone) and ventricular fibrillation (successfully treated) and ventricular tachycardia (timing not reported) in one patient each. he case series of 331 patients
[36] reported transient cardiac arrhythmia during the procedure, which was managed pharmacologically in 2 patients. ocal bleeding from the groin requiring readmission to the hospital occurred in four patients (including two patients with pseudoaneurysms successfully treated with thrombin injection). ne patient had minor gastrointestinal bleeding requiring hospitalization at 1 week. urgical removal of the balloon was required in one patient, and difficulty in removing the balloon or delivery system occurred in four patients. o deaths, cerebral strokes, severe bleeding or injury to the nerves were reported.
he whole body of data shows that there is inconclusive evidence on the efficacy of balloon angioplasty for  patients, mainly due to the observational design of the few small case series and their high risk of bias
[38]. he uncertainty surrounding  and  treatment means that it should be dealt with only as part of a properly designed randomized clinical trial. n official position statement put forth by the β€�onsiglio uperiore di anit. Γ ,β€� the scientific advisory board of the Italian Ministry of Health, recommends that study investigators β€�look at the prevalence and association of CCSVI with MS,β€� and states that β€�any test to assess benefits and risk of the treatment for CCSVI should only be carried out in the context of randomized controlled trials which would avoid any commercial conflict of interestβ€�
[39].
In March 2012, the National Institute for Health and Clinical Excellence (NICE) released guidance on percutaneous venoplasty for chronic cerebrospinal venous insufficiency for multiple sclerosis, stating β€�Current evidence on the efficacy of percutaneous venoplasty for CCSVI for MS is inadequate in quality and quantityβ€� and encouraging β€�further research on percutaneous venoplasty for CCSVI for MS, in the form of robust controlled clinical trials. Outcomes should include clinical and quality of life measuresβ€�
[38].
