[58,59]. or this reason, two primary end points were identified, one defined by a set of clinical instrumental parameters related to specific functional deficits experienced by patients with  and the other one based on  findings, both measured 12 months after randomization. he decision to utilize two primary end points emerged from various considerations. irst, the hypothesized effect of angioplasty for  patients with  does not allow exclusion of a clinical effect independent of the incidence of active  lesions. n the other hand,  parameters are largely utilized as indicators of activity in clinical trials for  and are considered robust with respect to any placebo effect. he observation of a statistically significant advantage in only one of the two end points (clinical or ) will be sufficient to declare the study results in favor of the superiority of angioplasty over sham procedure. n the event of conflicting results (active treatment favored by one end point and not favored by the other one), the combined clinical end point will prevail. econd, the use of two primary end points in this situation offers at least two advantages: (1) f masking of both participants and investigators succeeds, the demonstration of a significant effect of the treatment on even only one of the two end points would be sufficient to reject the hypothesis that venous angioplasty is not active or efficacious in patients with ; and (2) in the event that failure of the masking occurs, thus potentially weakening the evidence coming from the clinical end point, the evaluation of the  end point would maintain its validity entirely, thereby permitting the study to conserve, even if only partially, scientific and clinical usefulness.
