[47], the most widely used disability measure in clinical trials for , is an ambulation-centered scale that does not take into account cognitive impairment or upper-arm or bladder dysfunctions that are primary components of disability. he  is an ordinal nonlinear scale whose serial upward changes of 0.5 or 1.0 points, confirmed at 3β€“6 months or unconfirmed, are commonly used in clinical trials. owever, changes of 0.5 points are invalid, even if confirmed at 3 or 6 months, and, similarly, 1-point changes are not significantly more likely to occur for worsening than for improvement
